You could write an [extension](https://junit.org/junit5/docs/current/user-guide/#extensions) that:

1. Creates a new `SoftAssertions` instance before each test
2. Provides the created `SoftAssertions` as a parameter
3. Calls `assertAll()` after each test

Extension:

```java
public class SoftAssertionsExtension
		extends TypeBasedParameterResolver&lt;SoftAssertions&gt;
		implements BeforeTestExecutionCallback, AfterTestExecutionCallback {

	private static final Namespace STORE_NAMESPACE = Namespace.create(SoftAssertionsExtension.class);
	private static final String STORE_KEY = SoftAssertions.class.getSimpleName();

	@Override
	public void beforeTestExecution(ExtensionContext context) {
		context.getStore(STORE_NAMESPACE).put(STORE_KEY, new SoftAssertions());
	}

	@Override
	public void afterTestExecution(ExtensionContext context) {
		context.getStore(STORE_NAMESPACE).get(STORE_KEY, SoftAssertions.class).assertAll();
	}

	@Override
	public SoftAssertions resolveParameter(ParameterContext parameterContext, ExtensionContext extensionContext)
			throws ParameterResolutionException {
		return extensionContext.getStore(STORE_NAMESPACE).get(STORE_KEY, SoftAssertions.class);
	}

}
```

Usage:

```java
@ExtendWith(SoftAssertionsExtension.class)
class SoftAssertionsTest {

	@Test
	void passingTest(SoftAssertions softly) {
		softly.assertThat(true).isTrue();
	}

	@Test
	void failingTest(SoftAssertions softly) {
		softly.assertThat(true).isFalse();
	}

}
```

The test status is automatically set by the extension / `assertAll()` method.

